      <insight xml:id="idea_hyperbolic_log">
        <title>Logarithmic definitions of Inverse Hyperbolic Functions</title>
        <sidebyside>
          <ol cols="2">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\ds\cosh^{-1}x=\ln\big(x+\sqrt{x^2-1}\big);\ x\geq1</m><idx><h>hyperbolic function</h><h>inverse!logarithmic def.</h></idx>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\ds\tanh^{-1}x = \frac12\ln\left(\frac{1+x}{1-x}\right);\ |x|\lt 1</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\ds \sech^{-1}x = \ln\left(\frac{1+\sqrt{1-x^2}}x\right);\ 0\lt x\leq1</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\ds\sinh^{-1}x = \ln\big(x+\sqrt{x^2+1}\big)</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\ds\coth^{-1}x = \frac12\ln\left(\frac{x+1}{x-1}\right);\ |x|>1</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\ds\csch^{-1}x = \ln\left(\frac1x+\frac{\sqrt{1+x^2}}{|x|}\right);\ x\neq0</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </sidebyside>
      </insight>

    </sidebyside>

    <p>
      The following Key Ideas give the derivatives and integrals relating to the inverse hyperbolic functions.
      In <xref ref="idea_hyperbolic_inverse_integrals">Key Idea</xref>,
      both the inverse hyperbolic and logarithmic function representations of the antiderivative are given,
      based on <xref ref="idea_hyperbolic_log">Key Idea</xref>.
      Again, these latter functions are often more useful than the former.
      Note how inverse hyperbolic functions can be used to solve integrals we used Trigonometric Substitution to solve in <xref ref="sec_trig_sub">Section</xref>.
    </p>

    <insight xml:id="idea_hyperbolic_inverse_derivatives">
      <title>Derivatives Involving Inverse Hyperbolic Functions</title>
      <ol cols="2">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ds\frac{d}{dx}\big(\cosh^{-1} x\big) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2-1}};\ x>1</m><idx><h>derivative</h><h>inverse hyper.</h></idx><idx><h>hyperbolic function</h><h>inverse!derivative</h></idx>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ds\frac{d}{dx}\big(\sinh^{-1} x\big) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2+1}}</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ds\frac{d}{dx}\big(\tanh^{-1} x\big) = \frac{1}{1-x^2};\ |x|\lt 1</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ds\frac{d}{dx}\big(\sech^{-1} x\big) = \frac{-1}{x\sqrt{1-x^2}}; 0\lt x\lt 1</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ds\frac{d}{dx}\big(\csch^{-1} x\big) = \frac{-1}{|x|\sqrt{1+x^2}};\ x\neq0</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ds\frac{d}{dx}\big(\coth^{-1} x\big) = \frac{1}{1-x^2};\ |x|>1</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </insight>

    <p>
      \end{minipage}
    </p>

    <insight xml:id="idea_hyperbolic_inverse_integrals">
      <title>Integrals Involving Inverse Hyperbolic Functions</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ds\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2-a^2}}\ dx</m> <m>\ds=\qquad \cosh^{-1}\left(\frac xa\right)+C;\ 0\lt a\lt x</m>
            <m>\ds=\ln\Big|x+\sqrt{x^2-a^2}\Big|+C</m><idx><h>integration</h><h>inverse hyper.</h></idx><idx><h>hyperbolic function</h><h>inverse!integration</h></idx>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ds\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2+a^2}}\ dx</m>
            <m>\ds=\qquad \sinh^{-1}\left(\frac xa\right)+C;\ a>0</m> <m>\ds=\ln\Big|x+\sqrt{x^2+a^2}\Big|+C</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ds\int \frac{1}{a^2-x^2}\ dx</m>
            <m>\ds=\qquad \left\{\begin{array}{ccc} \frac1a\tanh^{-1}\left(\frac xa\right)+C \amp \amp x^2\lt a^2 \\ \\
            \frac1a\coth^{-1}\left(\frac xa\right)+C \amp \amp a^2\lt x^2
            \end{array} \right.</m> <m>\ds=\frac1{2a}\ln\left|\frac{a+x}{a-x}\right|+C</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ds\int \frac{1}{x\sqrt{a^2-x^2}}\ dx</m>
            <m>\ds=\qquad -\frac1a\sech^{-1}\left(\frac xa\right)+C;\ 0\lt x\lt a</m> <m>\ds= \frac1a \ln\left(\frac{x}{a+\sqrt{a^2-x^2}}\right)+C</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ds\int \frac{1}{x\sqrt{x^2+a^2}}\ dx</m>
            <m>\ds=\qquad -\frac1a\csch^{-1}\left|\frac xa\right| + C;\ x\neq 0,\ a>0</m><m>\ds= \frac1a \ln\left|\frac{x}{a+\sqrt{a^2+x^2}}\right|+C</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </insight>

    <p>
      \end{minipage}
    </p>

    <p>
      We practice using the derivative and integral formulas in the following example.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="ex_hf3">
      <title>Derivatives and integrals involving inverse hyperbolic functions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Evaluate the following.
        </p>

        <ol cols="2">
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\ds \frac{d}{dx}\left[\cosh^{-1}\left(\frac{3x-2}{5}\right)\right]</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\ds \int\frac{1}{x^2-1}\ dx</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\ds \int \frac{1}{\sqrt{9x^2+10}}\ dx</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Applying <xref ref="idea_hyperbolic_inverse_derivatives">Key Idea</xref> with the Chain Rule gives:
                <me>
                  \frac{d}{dx}\left[\cosh^{-1}\left(\frac{3x-2}5\right)\right] = \frac{1}{\sqrt{\left(\frac{3x-2}5\right)^2-1}}\cdot\frac35
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Multiplying the numerator and denominator by <m>(-1)</m> gives:
                <m>\ds \int \frac{1}{x^2-1}\ dx = \int \frac{-1}{1-x^2}\ dx</m>.
                The second integral can be solved with a direct application of item <hash />3 from <xref ref="idea_hyperbolic_inverse_integrals">Key Idea</xref>,
                with <m>a=1</m>.
                Thus
                <md>
                  <mrow>\int \frac{1}{x^2-1}\ dx \amp = -\int \frac{1}{1-x^2}\ dx</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \left\{\begin{array}{ccc} -\tanh^{-1}\left(x\right)+C \amp  \amp  x^2\lt 1</mrow>
                  <mrow>-\coth^{-1}\left(x\right)+C \amp  \amp  1\lt x^2 \end{array}\right.</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp =-\frac12\ln\left|\frac{x+1}{x-1}\right|+C</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp =\frac12\ln\left|\frac{x-1}{x+1}\right|+C</mrow>
                </md>.
                We should note that this exact problem was solved at the beginning of <xref ref="sec_partial_fraction">Section</xref>.
                In that example the answer was given as <m>\frac12\ln|x-1|-\frac12\ln|x+1|+C</m>.
                Note that this is equivalent to the answer given in <xref ref="eq_hf3">Equation</xref>,
                as <m>\ln(a/b) = \ln a - \ln b</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                This requires a substitution,
                then item <hash />2 of <xref ref="idea_hyperbolic_inverse_integrals">Key Idea</xref> can be applied.

                Let <m>u = 3x</m>, hence <m>du = 3dx</m>.
                We have
                <md>
                  <mrow>\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{9x^2+10}}\ dx \amp = \frac13\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{u^2+10}}\ du.</mrow>
                  <intertext>Note <m>a^2=10</m>, hence <m>a = \sqrt{10}</m>. Now apply the integral rule.</intertext>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac13 \sinh^{-1}\left(\frac{3x}{\sqrt{10}}\right) + C</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac13 \ln \Big|3x+\sqrt{9x^2+10}\Big|+C</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      This section covers a lot of ground.
      New functions were introduced,
      along with some of their fundamental identities,
      their derivatives and antiderivatives, their inverses,
      and the derivatives and antiderivatives of these inverses.
      Four Key Ideas were presented,
      each including quite a bit of information.
    </p>

    <p>
      Do not view this section as containing a source of information to be memorized,
      but rather as a reference for future problem solving.
      <xref ref="idea_hyperbolic_inverse_integrals">Key Idea</xref>
      contains perhaps the most useful information.
      Know the integration forms it helps evaluate and understand how to use the inverse hyperbolic answer and the logarithmic answer.
    </p>

    <p>
      The next section takes a brief break from demonstrating new integration techniques.
      It instead demonstrates a technique of evaluating limits that return indeterminate forms.
      This technique will be useful in <xref ref="sec_improper_integration">Section</xref>,
      where limits will arise in the evaluation of certain definite integrals.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Terms and Concepts</title>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In <xref ref="idea_hyperbolic_identities">Key Idea</xref>,
          the equation <m>\ds \int \tanh x\ dx = \ln (\cosh x)+C</m> is given.
          Why is <q><m>\ln |\cosh x|</m></q>
          not used <mdash /> i.e., why are absolute values not necessary?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          Because <m>\cosh x</m> is always positive.
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The hyperbolic functions are used to define points on the right hand portion of the hyperbola <m>x^2-y^2=1</m>,
          as shown in <xref ref="fig_hfcircle">Figure</xref>.
          How can we use the hyperbolic functions to define points on the left hand portion of the hyperbola?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          The points on the left hand side can be defined as <m>(-\cosh x, \sinh x)</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Problems</title>
    <p>
      In the following exercises,
      verify the given identity using <xref ref="def_hyperbolic_functions">Definition</xref>,
      as done in <xref ref="ex_hf1">Example</xref>.
    </p>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\coth^2 x-\csch^2x=1</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\begin{aligned}\coth^2x-\csch^2x \amp = \left(\frac{e^x+e^{-x}}{e^x-e^{-x}}\right)^2 - \left(\frac{2}{e^x-e^{-x}}\right)^2 \\
          \amp = \frac{(e^{2x} + 2 + e^{-2x}) - (4)}{e^{2x} - 2 + e^{-2x}}\\
          \amp = \frac{e^{2x} - 2 + e^{-2x}}{e^{2x} - 2 + e^{-2x}}\\
          \amp = 1
          \end{aligned}</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\cosh 2x = \cosh^2x+\sinh^2x</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\begin{aligned}\cosh^2x+\sinh^2x \amp = \left(\frac{e^x+e^{-x}}{2}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{e^x-e^{-x}}{2}\right)^2 \\
          \amp = \frac{e^{2x} + 2 + e^{-2x}}{4} + \frac{e^{2x} - 2 + e^{-2x}}{4}\\
          \amp = \frac{2e^{2x} + 2e^{-2x}}{4}\\
          \amp = \frac{e^{2x} + e^{-2x}}{2} \\
          \amp = \cosh 2x.
          \end{aligned}</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\ds\cosh^2x = \frac{\cosh2x+1}{2}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\begin{aligned}\cosh^2x \amp = \left(\frac{e^x+e^{-x}}{2}\right)^2 \\
          \amp = \frac{e^{2x} + 2 + e^{-2x}}{4} \\
          \amp = \frac12\frac{(e^{2x} + e^{-2x})+2}{2}\\
          \amp = \frac12\left(\frac{e^{2x} + e^{-2x}}{2}+1\right)\\
          \amp = \frac{\cosh2x+1}{2}.
          \end{aligned}</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\ds\sinh^2x = \frac{\cosh2x-1}{2}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\begin{aligned}\sinh^2x \amp = \left(\frac{e^x-e^{-x}}{2}\right)^2 \\
          \amp = \frac{e^{2x} - 2 + e^{-2x}}{4} \\
          \amp = \frac12\frac{(e^{2x} + e^{-2x})-2}{2}\\
          \amp = \frac12\left(\frac{e^{2x} + e^{-2x}}{2}-1\right)\\
          \amp = \frac{\cosh2x-1}{2}.
          \end{aligned}</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\ds\frac{d}{dx}\left[\sech x\right] = -\sech x\tanh x</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\begin{aligned}\frac{d}{dx}\left[\sech x\right] \amp = \frac{d}{dx}\left[\frac{2}{e^x+e^{-x}}\right] \\
          \amp = \frac{-2(e^x-e^{-x})}{(e^x+e^{-x})^2} \\
          \amp = -\frac{2(e^x-e^{-x})}{(e^x+e^{-x})(e^x+e^{-x})} \\
          \amp = -\frac{2}{e^x+e^{-x}}\cdot \frac{e^x-e^{-x}}{e^x+e^{-x}}\\
          \amp = -\sech x\tanh x
          \end{aligned}</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\ds\frac{d}{dx}\left[\coth x\right] = -\csch^2x</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\begin{aligned}\frac{d}{dx}\left[\coth x\right] \amp = \frac{d}{dx}\left[\frac{e^x+e^{-x}}{e^x-e^{-x}}\right] \\
          \amp = \frac{(e^x-e^{-x})(e^x-e^{-x})-(e^x+e^{-x})(e^x+e^{-x})}{(e^x-e^{-x})^2}\\
          \amp = \frac{e^{2x}+e^{-2x} - 2 - (e^{2x}+e^{-2x}+2)}{(e^x-e^{-x})^2}\\
          \amp = -\frac{4}{(e^x-e^{-x})^2}\\
          \amp =-\csch^2x
          \end{aligned}</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\ds \int \tanh x\ dx = \ln (\cosh x) + C</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\ds \int \tanh x\ dx = \int \frac{\sinh x}{\cosh x}\ dx</m>
        </p>

        <p>
          Let <m>u = \cosh x</m>; <m>du = (\sinh x) dx</m>
        </p>

        <p>
          <m>\begin{aligned}\amp = \int \frac{1}{u}\ du \\
          \amp = \ln |u| + C \\
          \amp = \ln (\cosh x) + C.
          \end{aligned}</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\ds \int \coth x\ dx = \ln |\sinh x| + C</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\begin{aligned}\int \coth x\ dx \amp = \int \frac{\cosh x}{\sinh x}\ dx\\
          \text{ Let \(u = \sinh x\); \(du = (\cosh x) dx\) } \\
          \amp = \int \frac{1}{u}\ du \\
          \amp = \ln |u| + C \\
          \amp = \ln |\sinh x| + C.
          \end{aligned}</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>

    <p>
      In the following exercises, find the derivative of the given function.
    </p>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>f(x) = \cosh 2x</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
